It's not part of my main job but a side project with a professor of mine. Basically I had a thesis way back about computing the skyline out of a set of 2D points in the new cluster computing technology Apache Spark, I was done with that fairly fast (all in Java not Scala) then we said to continue it (separately from uni) in order to make our own algorithm optimized for Spark and then publish it as a scientific article and I am working on pretty much optimizing it as much as possible. 

I liked doing this because the skyline is quite interesting, simply said imagine you are booking a vacation on my website for Hawai for example and you want to get the best out of your money and be as close to the beach as possible. So your X is the money and Y is the distance from the beach, what I should do is that out of the millions of hotels I should present you your best bang for your buck so basically pay as little money for as little distance from the beach so I need to find only those "points" that are not "dominated" by others. For example you have Hotel1(x=$50, y=100meters) and Hotel2(x=$41, y=80meters), Hotel2 is better at every case compared to Hotel1 so it dominates Hotel1 thus Hotel1 is not part of the skyline.
Big Data is indeed awesome, seeing a (relatively) small change in your code making 8 computers using 30% less CPU is pretty much translating directly to "I just saved some money" :stuck_out_tongue:
